1. Accounting
The process of recording, analyzing, classifying, and interpreting the financial data of a business entity is known as accounting. Accounting assists in describing the position and performance of a company in an appropriate manner. With the help of accounting, a business can keep proper records of its revenues, expenditures, and liabilities. These details are important for decision-makers as they provide necessary details about the activities of the firm. In general, accounting can be considered the “language of business” since it helps to communicate financial details to the users.
Objectives of Accounting 
The main objective of accounting is to provide accurate and reliable financial information about a business. It helps in determining profit or loss during a specific period and showing the financial position through balance sheets. Accounting also aims to maintain systematic records of all transactions, ensuring transparency and accountability. Another important objective is to assist management in planning and decision-making by providing useful financial data. It also helps in safeguarding assets, preventing fraud, and meeting legal requirements such as tax filing and reporting. 
Scope of Accounting 
It is wide and covers various areas related to financial management and reporting. It includes financial accounting, which deals with recording and preparing financial statements for external users. Cost accounting focuses on cost control and efficient use of resources. Management accounting provides information for internal decision-making and planning. The scope also extends to auditing, which ensures accuracy and reliability of financial records, and taxation, which involves calculation and payment of taxes. 
Advantages of Accounting
Accounting offers several benefits to businesses and stakeholders. It ensures systematic record-keeping of all financial transactions, making it easier to track income and expenses. It helps in determining profit or loss and evaluating the financial health of the company. Accounting provides valuable information for decision-making, planning, and control of business operations. It also ensures legal compliance with tax laws and financial regulations. Additionally, accounting helps in detecting fraud, safeguarding assets, and improving financial discipline. For investors and creditors, accounting information is useful in assessing the performance and reliability of a business before making investment decisions.
Limitations of Accounting
Despite its advantages, accounting has certain limitations. It is mainly based on historical data, which may not always reflect the current or future financial situation. Accounting does not consider qualitative factors such as employee skills, brand value, or market conditions, which also affect business performance. It relies on certain principles and estimates, which may involve personal judgment and can lead to bias. Moreover, accounting information may sometimes be manipulated if not properly monitored. It also focuses only on monetary transactions and ignores non-financial aspects. 
Basic Terminologies in Accounting 
These are essential for understanding financial statements. Assets are resources owned by the business, such as cash, buildings, and machinery. Liabilities are obligations or debts owed to outsiders. Capital refers to the owner’s investment in the business. Revenue is the income earned from business activities, while expenses are the costs incurred to earn that income. Profit is the excess of revenue over expenses, whereas loss occurs when expenses exceed revenue. Other terms include accounts, transactions, and financial statements, which help in recording and presenting financial information clearly and systematically.

2. Accounting Concepts and Conventions with examples.
Accounting concepts and conventions provide the basic framework for recording, preparing, and presenting financial information in a clear and consistent way. These principles ensure that financial statements are understandable, reliable, and comparable across different periods and organizations.
Accounting Concepts
Accounting concepts are the fundamental assumptions on which accounting is based. One of the most important is the business entity concept, which treats the business as separate from its owner. For example, if the owner invests ₹50,000, it is recorded as capital, not as income. The going concern concept assumes that the business will continue its operations for the foreseeable future, so assets are valued at cost rather than their liquidation value.
The Money Measurement Concept states that only those transactions that can be expressed in monetary terms are recorded. For instance, the purchase of machinery is recorded, but employee efficiency is not. The dual-aspect concept explains that every transaction has two effects—one debit and one credit. For example, purchasing goods for cash increases inventory and reduces cash. Another important concept is the Matching Concept, which ensures that expenses are recorded in the same period as the revenues they help generate, such as paying salaries in the month they are earned. The accounting period concept divides the life of a business into fixed time periods, such as a year, for reporting purposes.
Accounting Conventions 
Accounting conventions are generally accepted practices followed by accountants to ensure consistency and clarity. The Convention of Conservatism advises recording all expected losses but not anticipated profits. For example, provision for doubtful debts is created even before the loss is confirmed. The Convention of Consistency ensures that the same accounting methods are followed every year, such as using the same method of depreciation, which helps in comparing performance over time.
The Convention of Full Disclosure requires that all material facts must be clearly presented in the financial statements. For example, details about loans, liabilities, or legal issues should be disclosed. The Convention of Materiality states that only significant information should be given importance. Small expenses such as minor stationery costs can be grouped together rather than shown separately. Accounting concepts provide the theoretical base for recording and analysing financial transactions, while conventions offer practical guidelines for their application. Together, they help ensure accuracy, transparency, and consistency in financial reporting, enabling stakeholders to make informed decisions.
3. Accounting Policies
Accounting policies refer to the specific principles, rules, and methods adopted by a business while preparing its financial statements. These policies guide how transactions are recorded, measured, and presented, ensuring consistency and clarity in reporting. For example, a company may choose a particular method of depreciation, such as the straight-line method, or a specific method of inventory valuation like FIFO or LIFO. Accounting policies may differ between organizations, but they must follow accepted standards and be disclosed clearly in financial reports. Proper accounting policies help users understand financial statements and compare performance over different periods.
Accounting Standards
The formal guidelines issued by recognized authorities to ensure consistency, transparency, and comparability in financial reporting. These standards provide rules on how financial transactions should be recorded and presented. They are mandatory for companies to follow to maintain uniformity across industries and countries. For example, standards prescribe how revenue should be recognized or how assets should be valued. Accounting standards improve the reliability of financial statements and help investors, creditors, and regulators make informed decisions. They also reduce confusion by ensuring that similar transactions are treated in the same way across different organizations.
GAAP (Generally Accepted Accounting Principles) 
GAAP refers to a set of accounting principles, standards, and procedures that companies follow while preparing financial statements, particularly in countries like the United States. These principles ensure accuracy, consistency, and comparability of financial reports. GAAP includes concepts such as revenue recognition, matching of expenses, and full disclosure. For example, under GAAP, revenue is recorded when it is earned, not when cash is received. GAAP helps stakeholders understand the financial condition of a company and compare it with others. It also provides a common framework that increases trust in financial reporting among investors and regulators.
IFRS (International Financial Reporting Standards) 
IFRS are global accounting standards developed by the International Accounting Standards Board (IASB) to bring uniformity in financial reporting across different countries. These standards help companies present their financial statements in a consistent and comparable format internationally. IFRS focuses more on principles rather than strict rules, allowing flexibility in application. For example, IFRS provides guidelines for revenue recognition, asset valuation, and lease accounting. Many countries have adopted IFRS or converged their standards with it. The main advantage of IFRS is that it facilitates global investment and comparison of financial statements across international businesses.
Changes in Accounting Policies 
It occurs when a company adopts a different accounting method or principle from the one previously used. Such changes may be required due to new accounting standards or legal requirements or to present financial information more accurately. For example, a company may change its depreciation method or inventory valuation approach. When changes are made, they must be clearly disclosed in financial statements along with the reason and impact of the change. This ensures transparency and helps users understand differences in financial results over time. Proper disclosure maintains trust and consistency in financial reporting.

